"{\"uid\": \"straitstimes.com-sport-tennis-olympic-champ-zheng-staying-grounded-to-avoid-post-paris-letdown\", \"text\": \"Choose edition  Search  singapore  asia  world  opinion  life  business  sport  Visual  Podcasts  SPH Rewards  STClassifieds  Paid press releases  Advertise with us  FAQs  Contact us  Sign up now:Get the biggest sports news in your inbox  China's Olympic champion Zheng Qinwen in her match against Amanda Anisimova at the US Open.  PHOTO: REUTERS  Published\\u00c2Aug 27, 2024, 10:33 AM  Updated\\u00c2Aug 27, 2024, 09:23 PM  NEW YORK\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093China\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Zheng Qinwen is refusing to let history repeat itself, as she hopes for a deep run at the US Open after claiming her country\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s first Olympic tennis singles gold in Paris.  The 21-year-old has in the past followed big tournaments with sub-par showings, a fate that she would need to avoid if she wants to win her first Grand Slam.  Zheng cleared the first hurdle on Aug 26 as she battled back from a set down to defeat Amanda Anisimova of the United States 4-6, 6-4, 6-2 in New York.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s the typical match I will lose, especially after huge success, because I know myself. Usually after huge success, I will get a little bit too high,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she said.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cSo this time when I get a success, I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m telling myself, I don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t want to let this happen (again). I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m going to continue working hard, keep the stable mindset.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  The Chinese star is no stranger to stumbling soon after soaring in the biggest moments.  Her quarter-final appearance at the 2023 US Open was followed by a first-round exit at the China Open. And after reaching the Australian Open final this season, she suffered a sub-par performance at the Qatar Open.  After her victory against Anisimova, an on-court interviewer lauded Zheng\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Olympic achievement, but she was quick to say she was looking ahead.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cTo come to the next tournament (after the Games), everything starts (at) zero. You are not any more Olympic champion. Just be humble and try to work, fight every single match. Because if you don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t fight, you have a big chance you lose,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Zheng added.  Anisimova had arrived in New York on the upswing. She was ranked 373rd in the world when she returned from a mental health break in January. But a run to the final at Toronto in August saw her return to the top 50 and gain a wildcard invitation into the main draw at Flushing Meadows.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cEvery ball (from Anisimova) went inside in the beginning and I couldn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t do anything,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Zheng admitted, referring to the first set.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cAs the match goes, I started to find my rhythm... Little by little I started to get into the rhythm.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m really happy to get this match, because she\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s really tough to face. Like you see, she\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in the final of Toronto. I think one of her best surfaces is on hard court.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cTo (have) won this match means I make one step forward in my mental side.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Zheng will next face Russian Erika Andreeva in the second round.REUTERS, AFP  US Open (Tennis)  Grand Slam  Olympics 2024  China  E-paper  Newsletters  Podcasts  RSS Feed  About Us  Terms & Conditions  Personal Data Protection Notice  Need help? Reach us here.  Advertise with us    \"}"